[1] Viet Nam, H5N1
Date: Fri 16 Jul 2004
From: Luiz Jacintho da Silva <ljsilva@promedmail.org>
Source: ABC Online [Australia], 16 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200407/s1155030.htm>

More bird flu outbreaks in Viet Nam
----------------------------------
Bird flu is suspected of spreading to an 8th province in Viet Nam, but
officials have insisted fresh outbreaks of the disease were under control.
Veterinary officials in the southern coastal province of Ba Ria-Vung Tau
said hundreds of chickens and ducks had died since 6 Jul 2004, particularly
in and around the town of Vung Tau.
Blood samples from the dead poultry were sent last week [1st week July
2004] to the southern regional veterinary department in Ho Chi Minh City to
test for the presence of the lethal H5N1 strain of bird flu. The results
are yet to be released.
If presence of the virus is confirmed, Ba Ria-Vung Tau would be the 8th
province to be affected by bird flu after the government's highly
criticized 30 Mar 2004 declaration that the country was free of the disease.
The announcement, which came just 15 days after the disease claimed its
16th fatality, prompted charges from international disease control experts
that Hanoi was acting prematurely and recklessly.
The World Health Organization (WHO) has warned that it could take years to
eliminate the virus from the environment.
New outbreaks have also been reported in the southern Mekong Delta province
of Tra Vinh, one of the 7 provinces confirmed by the government to be
facing a recurrence of the disease. Local veterinary officials said
thousands of quail had died since the end of June 2004, with the Cang Long
district among the worst affected.
3 districts in Can Tho province, also in the Delta region, are also
tackling fresh outbreaks.
Provincial authorities have ordered the setting up of isolation zones
around the areas of infection, the state-run Quan Doi Nhan Dan newspaper
reported.
According to the latest report from the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural
Development, more than 35 000 chickens and ducks, and 13 000 quail, have
been infected, culled, or have died as a result of the virus since April
2004. However, ministry spokesman Bui Quang Anh insisted the situation was
under control. "Viet Nam is able to control the return of the bird flu
epidemic," he told the Tuoi Tre newspaper.
Besides Viet Nam, Thailand and China have also reported fresh outbreaks in
recent weeks.
