[4] Indonesia: mass vaccination proposed
Date: Fri 16 Jul 2004
From: Debora MacKenzie <d.mackenzie@chello.be>
Source: The Jakarta Post, 16 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailcity.asp?fileid=20040716.G04&irec=3>

IPB, Japan to produce bird flu super vaccine
--------------------------------------------
The Veterinary School of the Bogor Institute of Agriculture (IPB), and the
institute's firm, PT Bogor Life Science and Technology, have cooperated
with Japan's Shigeta Animal Pharmaceuticals Inc. to develop a new vaccine
to prevent the deadly bird flu.
Shigeta director Yoshiyuki Nishio, and PT Bogor Life director Thamrin
Poeloengan, signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) on Wed 14 Jul 2004.
The team will work on an avian flu recombinant vaccine, which is claimed to
be a modification of the existing vaccines currently used widely to deal
with outbreaks of the H5N1 bird flu virus that ravaged Asian flocks since
early 2004.
Many experts said the existing vaccines could not prevent humans from being
infected by the virus.
PT Bogor Life operational director Kamaluddin Zarkasie said that, to work
effectively, the new vaccine was the molecular modification of an organism
that has high endurance. "Moreover, the vaccine is made from an inactive
virus, so that it will be much safer than the existing one, which uses live
viruses," he said, after the signing at the Veterinary School Hall. [Though
this might be interpreted as a live-attenuated vaccine, Zarkasie probably
refers here to the use of a live virus during the 1st stages of the
production of existing inactivated vaccines. ProMED-mail has, in the past,
mentioned rumors of the use of live AI vaccines in East Asia, but, no
confirmation could be obtained. - Mod.AS]. "We need the vaccine, because
Indonesia has many poultry farms, with about 1 billion fowl," he added.
Although no cases in humans have been found in Indonesia, 7.4 million
chickens, ducks, geese, pigeons, and other birds were estimated to have
died from the disease, and thousands of others culled to prevent the virus
from spreading.
Ironically, as the central government, and the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) have revealed, bird flu could have been
brought into the country via illegal vaccines, possibly from China, Mexico
or Italy. Human error is presumed to have resulted in the presence of whole
live viruses in the illegal [allegedly inactivated] vaccines.
FAO also suspected the virus was brought in through illegally imported
livestock, and livestock products, which are widespread in Indonesia.
According to Kamaluddin, the team will produce 300 million dosages of the
vaccine. "The 1st round of production will be carried out by Shigeta, which
has the infrastructure. We shall produce it ourselves after we have all the
facilities, maybe next year," he explained. In the future, he added, PT
Bogor Life would have the right to sell the vaccine to other neighboring
countries vulnerable to the disease, including Malaysia, Myanmar, Thailand,
the Philippines, and Viet Nam.
[Byline: Theresia Sufa]
--
Debora MacKenzie
<d.mackenzie@chello.be>
[The information supplied by Shigeta, and PT Bogor Life, on other vaccines,
allegedly in use, deserve attention. They say that the FAO has revealed
that bird flu could have been brought into Indonesia via illegal (killed)
vaccines, which might have included whole live viruses. If true, and
provided a classical stamping-out policy is not applicable under
the prevailing Indonesian conditions, then "Targeted and strictly
monitored vaccination, using a quality-assured, vaccine remains a
complementary option" (as indicated by the FAO; see 20040715.1917).
However, general, mass vaccination of the national poultry population is
another story. It will be interesting to note the opinion on such a
strategy by the advisory expert panels of the relevant international
organizations. It will also be of importance to note whether the
vaccination plan, presented by the 2 institutions above, is acceptable, or,
has been endorsed by the Indonesian authorities.
The pros and cons of various vaccination policies have been discussed in a
paper by Capua and Marangon (see ref 20040325.0829).
In a recent paper -- by Lee et al, Effect of Vaccine Use in the Evolution
of Mexican-Lineage H5N2 Avian Influenza Virus (to be published in the
Journal of Virology on 1 Aug 2004) -- experience and observations gathered
during 8 years have been discussed. Examination of the commercial vaccine
and viruses isolated from Mexico over the past 8 years showed the same
types of changes that were observed in humans. It has been demonstrated
that veterinary influenza vaccines, like human vaccines, should
be reconsidered yearly for updates to achieve optimal protection, since
antigenic drift may take place. - Mod.AS].
